# 5. Executive Summary

Procurement is one of the few business functions that touches every department in an organization, yet it is frequently the most under-invested area from a systems and tooling perspective. Finance has ERP systems. Sales has CRM platforms. HR has dedicated HRMS tools. Procurement, in a large number of small and mid-sized organizations, continues to run on a patchwork of spreadsheets, email threads, and manual sign-off chains that were never designed to scale beyond a handful of vendors and a handful of requests per month.

VendorHub — formally, the Enterprise Vendor & Procurement Management Platform — is proposed to close this gap. It consolidates the entire procurement lifecycle, from vendor onboarding through purchase order fulfillment and vendor performance evaluation, into a single, auditable, role-governed system of record. The platform is deliberately structured around the actual sequence of decisions a procurement team makes in practice: identify a need, raise a purchase request, secure approval, solicit quotations from qualified vendors, compare submissions on a like-for-like basis, select a vendor, formalize the commitment through a purchase order, track delivery, and evaluate the vendor relationship to inform future sourcing decisions.

This document sets out, in business terms, the rationale, scope, stakeholders, requirements, risks, and expected outcomes of VendorHub. It intentionally excludes implementation-level detail — data models, API contracts, UI wireframes, deployment topology — which are addressed in the subsequent System Requirement Specification (SRS), High-Level Design (HLD), and Low-Level Design (LLD) documents. The purpose of this BRD is to establish *what problem is being solved, for whom, and why it matters*, in language that a business stakeholder can evaluate and sign off on without needing to interpret technical artifacts, and in a manner precise enough that every downstream technical decision can be traced back to a documented business need.

VendorHub is not positioned as a generic record-keeping application. It is positioned as a decision-support and governance layer over procurement — a system that makes vendor selection defensible, purchase order issuance traceable, and vendor performance measurable over time, in a way that spreadsheets and email were never built to support.

---

# 6. Why VendorHub?

Naming and framing a platform correctly is not a cosmetic exercise; it shapes how stakeholders, users, and future adopters understand what the system is for. This section explains the reasoning behind the product name and the broader rationale for why an organization would choose to adopt it.

**Why this name.** The name "VendorHub" is intentionally literal. A "hub," in both common usage and enterprise software terminology, refers to a central point through which multiple parties converge and interact. In the procurement context, this is precisely the operational role the platform is designed to fill: internal departments, procurement managers, approvers, and external vendors all converge on a single system rather than communicating through scattered, disconnected channels. The name signals, without requiring further explanation, that this is a centralizing system — one designed to be the single place procurement activity happens, rather than one more tool alongside email and spreadsheets.

**Why this product.** VendorHub was conceived not as a speculative feature set but as a direct, traceable response to a well-documented and recurring operational failure mode: organizations that outgrow manual, spreadsheet-and-email procurement but are not yet large enough — or ready — to justify the cost, complexity, and implementation timeline of a Tier-1 enterprise Source-to-Pay suite such as SAP Ariba or Coupa. Every capability in VendorHub's scope maps directly to a specific, named pain point in the existing manual process (see Section 9), rather than existing simply because comparable products offer it. This traceability is what distinguishes a purpose-built solution from a feature checklist.

**How the name reflects procurement.** Beyond the "hub" metaphor, the full product name — VendorHub, Enterprise Vendor & Procurement Management Platform — makes explicit that the system addresses two related but distinct concerns: the *vendor relationship* (who the organization's suppliers are, and how reliable they have proven to be) and the *procurement process* (how a need becomes a purchase order). Many procurement tools focus narrowly on one or the other — either a vendor directory with no workflow, or a purchase-order tool with no vendor performance history. VendorHub is deliberately designed to unify both, because in practice, vendor selection and procurement workflow are inseparable decisions.

**Why organizations would adopt it.** Organizations adopt VendorHub not because procurement digitization is fashionable, but because the cost of *not* digitizing compounds quietly over time — in duplicate vendor records, in purchase requests that stall in inboxes, in quotation comparisons that consume hours of manual effort, and in an inability to answer basic leadership questions about spend and vendor reliability without a manual audit. VendorHub offers a proportionate response: enough structure and governance to solve these problems decisively, without the implementation overhead of an enterprise suite built for a scale most mid-sized organizations do not yet operate at.

---

# 7. Business Background

Procurement, by its nature, sits at the intersection of cost control, supplier relationships, and organizational risk. Every purchase an organization makes — from office supplies to critical raw materials or professional services — carries with it questions of value for money, vendor reliability, and internal accountability. Historically, organizations without dedicated procurement software have relied on a combination of email correspondence, shared spreadsheets, and informal verbal approvals to manage this function, largely because no purpose-built alternative was made available to them at a proportionate cost and complexity.

This informal approach works, in a limited sense, when an organization is small and the volume of purchase activity is low. A single procurement officer can reasonably keep track of five or ten vendors in a spreadsheet, and email is a perfectly adequate channel when only a handful of approvals are in flight at any given time. The moment an organization scales — more departments raising purchase requests, more vendors competing for business, more purchase orders in flight simultaneously — the informal system begins to break down in predictable and well-documented ways. Approvals get lost in crowded inboxes. The same vendor gets onboarded twice under slightly different names or contact details. Quotations are compared by manually copying figures between emails into a spreadsheet, a process that is both slow and prone to transcription error. There is no single place where a finance controller or an operations head can ask, "what are we currently spending with Vendor X across the organization," and receive an immediate, reliable answer.

VendorHub emerges directly from this operational reality. It is not conceived as a theoretical exercise but as a response to a class of problems that repeats itself, with remarkable consistency, across procurement teams in manufacturing, retail, IT services, healthcare, and logistics organizations of comparable scale. The project treats procurement not as a back-office administrative task but as a business process with measurable inputs (purchase requests), defined decision points (quotation comparison and vendor selection), and quantifiable outputs (purchase orders and delivered goods or services) — each of which benefits meaningfully from structured, system-enforced digital tracking rather than informal coordination.

---

# 8. Industry Overview

The vendor and procurement management software category sits within the broader Source-to-Pay (S2P) and Supplier Relationship Management (SRM) landscape. At the enterprise end of the market, established platforms such as SAP Ariba, Coupa, and Oracle Procurement Cloud offer extensive, highly configurable functionality, but this breadth comes at a corresponding cost — long implementation cycles measured in months, substantial licensing expenditure, and a degree of configurability that frequently exceeds what a mid-sized organization actually requires on day one. These platforms are architected for global enterprises managing thousands of suppliers across multiple geographies, currencies, and regulatory regimes, and their value proposition is genuinely realized at that scale.

At the other end of the spectrum, many small and mid-sized organizations operate with no procurement system at all. They either continue with entirely manual processes, or they attempt to force-fit procurement tracking into general-purpose tools — spreadsheets, generic ticketing systems, or basic task boards — that were never designed for the specific, sequential workflow of purchase requests, RFQs, quotation comparison, and purchase order issuance. These general-purpose tools can approximate parts of the workflow, but none of them natively enforce the relationships between a request, its approval, the resulting RFQ, the vendor quotations received, and the eventual purchase order.

This creates a clearly visible gap in the market: organizations that have outgrown spreadsheets but are not yet ready — operationally, organizationally, or financially — for a full enterprise S2P suite. VendorHub is deliberately positioned to serve this middle segment. It focuses on the core procurement lifecycle rather than attempting to replicate the full breadth of a Tier-1 enterprise suite, which allows it to be simpler to adopt, materially faster to roll out, and more directly aligned with what a procurement team actually needs day to day — visibility, accountability, and structured comparison — rather than, for example, multi-entity global tax configuration or complex approval-matrix customization that most mid-sized organizations will never use.

The broader industry trend also favors this positioning. Procurement digitization has accelerated meaningfully across mid-market organizations in recent years, as finance and operations leaders increasingly demand auditability of spend decisions — particularly in regulated, investor-backed, or audit-sensitive environments where "who approved this purchase, and on what basis" needs to be answerable with documented evidence, not institutional recollection.

---

# 9. Business Problem Statement

Organizations that manage procurement through spreadsheets, email, and manual paperwork consistently encounter a specific and recurring set of operational failures. These are not hypothetical concerns raised for the purposes of this document; they are the direct, observable consequences of running a multi-step, multi-stakeholder workflow without a system of record, and they were the primary input into the scoping decisions described later in this BRD.

**Duplicate and inconsistent vendor records.** When vendor information lives across individual spreadsheets maintained independently by different procurement staff, the same vendor is frequently onboarded more than once, under slightly different names, contact details, or tax identifiers. This fragments purchase history and makes it effectively impossible to obtain an accurate, consolidated picture of total spend with any single vendor.

**Slow, untracked approvals.** A purchase request submitted by email for approval has no enforced state. It can sit unread in an inbox for days without escalation. The requester has no reliable way to know whether it is pending, under active review, or simply forgotten, and the organization has no automatic mechanism to flag requests that have stalled beyond an acceptable turnaround.

**Manual quotation comparison.** When vendor quotations arrive as email attachments in inconsistent formats — differing layouts, differing units, differing terms — someone must manually transcribe pricing, delivery timelines, and terms into a comparison sheet before a decision can be made. This is both time-consuming and error-prone, and transcription errors at this stage directly influence which vendor is ultimately selected.

**Poor procurement visibility.** Without a central system, leadership has no real-time answer to basic operational questions: How many purchase requests are currently open? Which purchase orders are overdue for delivery? What is total spend this quarter, broken down by department or category? These questions currently require a manual, retrospective compilation exercise rather than an on-demand query.

**Lack of analytics.** Spreadsheet-based tracking does not naturally produce trend data. Organizations cannot easily identify their most reliable vendors, their slowest-approving departments, or categories of spend that are growing disproportionately, because the underlying data was never captured in a structured, analyzable form to begin with.

**Poor vendor performance tracking.** Vendor reliability — on-time delivery performance, quality of goods or services, responsiveness to communication — is rarely tracked systematically under the manual approach. As a result, vendor selection decisions frequently rely on informal reputation and recollection rather than a documented performance history that could be objectively reviewed.

**Human error and time-consuming paperwork.** Manual, repetitive data entry across purchase requests, RFQs, and purchase orders introduces avoidable errors and consumes procurement staff time that could otherwise be directed toward vendor negotiation, cost optimization, and strategic sourcing initiatives.

Each of these problems compounds the others rather than existing in isolation. A duplicate vendor record makes performance tracking meaningless, because performance data is split across multiple records for what is actually a single vendor. A slow, untracked approval process delays RFQ issuance downstream. Poor visibility means a problem is often not discovered until it has already caused a delay or a cost overrun, rather than being flagged proactively. VendorHub is designed to address this interconnected problem set as a whole, rather than solving any single symptom while leaving the others unaddressed.

---

# 10. Existing System

In the absence of a dedicated procurement platform, the "existing system" in most target organizations is, in practice, a loose combination of the following components, none of which were purpose-built for procurement:

- **Spreadsheets** (typically Excel or Google Sheets) used to maintain vendor lists, track purchase requests, and manually build quotation comparison tables, usually maintained independently by different individuals with limited cross-visibility.
- **Email** as the primary channel for requesting approvals, sending RFQs to vendors, and receiving vendor quotations, with no structured status tracking beyond whatever the individual user manually maintains.
- **Verbal or informal approvals**, particularly for lower-value purchases, where a manager's nod, a phone call, or a chat message substitutes for a documented, retrievable decision.
- **Paper-based or scanned purchase orders**, generated manually in a word processor and emailed or physically handed to the vendor, with no systematic linkage back to the request or quotation that justified them.
- **Ad hoc vendor rating**, where it exists at all, usually confined to informal team discussion in a meeting rather than a recorded, retrievable score tied to a specific vendor and order.

This existing system is not the result of poor planning on the part of procurement teams; it is simply what emerges organically when no purpose-built alternative is made available. It functions, in a basic sense — purchases do get made, vendors do get paid, goods do get delivered — but it functions without structure, without a reliable audit trail, and without the ability to scale gracefully as purchase volume and organizational complexity grow.

---

# 11. Drawbacks of Existing System

The existing spreadsheet-and-email approach carries drawbacks that extend well beyond simple inconvenience, and that become progressively more damaging as an organization scales:

**No single source of truth.** Vendor data, purchase request status, and quotation history are scattered across individual mailboxes and personal spreadsheet copies. When a procurement staff member is on leave or transitions out of the organization, their in-progress work is often effectively inaccessible to colleagues, creating operational continuity risk.

**No enforced workflow.** Nothing in the manual system technically prevents a purchase order from being issued before a purchase request has actually been approved, or before quotations have been properly compared. The integrity of the process depends entirely on individual staff discipline rather than system-level enforcement, which is an inherently fragile control mechanism.

**No audit trail.** If a vendor selection decision is later questioned — for instance, why a more expensive vendor was chosen over a lower-cost alternative — reconstructing the reasoning from scattered emails and informal notes is slow, and the reconstructed record is often incomplete or ambiguous.

**No real-time reporting.** Producing a spend report requires manually consolidating data from multiple spreadsheets, a task typically performed only periodically (monthly or quarterly) rather than being available on demand when leadership actually needs the information.

**Version control problems.** When multiple people edit the same shared spreadsheet, conflicting versions and accidental overwrites are common, particularly for shared vendor master lists that several staff members access concurrently.

**No role-based access control.** Anyone with access to a shared drive or spreadsheet can typically view or edit all procurement data, regardless of whether they should be authorized to see sensitive vendor pricing information or approve purchases above a certain threshold.

**Delayed vendor communication.** Vendors have no self-service way to view open RFQs or submit quotations directly; they depend entirely on being individually emailed by procurement staff, which slows the entire quotation-gathering step and introduces the risk that a qualified vendor is simply overlooked.

These drawbacks are the direct and specific justification for the proposed system described in the following sections. Each one maps to a corresponding capability in VendorHub's scope, as detailed in Section 16.

---

# 12. Proposed System

VendorHub proposes a centralized, role-governed web application that digitizes the complete procurement lifecycle described in the Business Workflow (Section 24). Rather than treating vendor management, purchase requests, RFQs, quotations, and purchase orders as separate, loosely connected activities — as the manual process effectively does — VendorHub models them as stages of a single continuous process, where each stage produces data that flows directly and traceably into the next.

At its core, the proposed system replaces:

- Spreadsheet-based vendor lists with a structured, de-duplicated vendor master record.
- Email-based approval chains with a system-tracked purchase request approval workflow that has an enforced, visible state at every stage.
- Manually emailed RFQs with a structured RFQ issuance and vendor quotation submission process, accessible to vendors through a dedicated self-service portal.
- Manually built comparison spreadsheets with structured, side-by-side quotation comparison presented consistently regardless of how individual vendors originally formatted their submissions.
- Word-processor purchase orders with system-generated, traceable purchase orders linked directly back to their originating request and the quotation that justified vendor selection.
- Informal vendor reputation with a structured, recorded vendor rating history that accumulates over time and across multiple completed orders.
- Periodic manual reporting with a real-time procurement dashboard, available on demand rather than compiled retrospectively.

The system is built around three primary user roles — Admin, Procurement Manager, and Vendor — each with access scoped precisely to their responsibilities, ensuring that sensitive procurement data, such as competing vendor pricing, is never exposed beyond those explicitly authorized to see it.

Architecturally, VendorHub follows a modular monolithic design using the MVC pattern with a dedicated service layer for business logic, built on the MERN stack (MongoDB, Express.js, React.js, Node.js). This architectural choice — deliberately not a microservices approach — reflects a decision to prioritize development speed, operational simplicity, and long-term maintainability appropriate to the scale of the target organization, rather than over-engineering the system for a distributed-systems scale it does not currently operate at. Detailed architectural rationale is addressed in the accompanying technical documentation; this BRD is concerned only with the business justification for the system's capabilities.

---

# 13. Business Objectives

The business objectives of VendorHub define the specific, measurable outcomes the organization expects the platform to deliver:

1. **Establish a single, authoritative vendor master record** that eliminates duplicate and inconsistent vendor data across the organization, ensuring every vendor exists as exactly one traceable record.
2. **Enforce a structured, trackable approval workflow** for purchase requests, so that every request has a visible, current status and a named, accountable approver at all times.
3. **Standardize the RFQ and quotation process** so that vendors respond in a consistent, comparable format rather than free-form email attachments.
4. **Reduce the time required to compare vendor quotations** by replacing manual spreadsheet transcription with structured, system-driven, side-by-side comparison.
5. **Provide end-to-end traceability from purchase request through to purchase order**, so that every purchase order can be linked directly back to the approved request and the quotation that justified vendor selection.
6. **Introduce a formal vendor performance rating mechanism** so that vendor selection is informed by recorded, retrievable history rather than informal recollection.
7. **Deliver real-time procurement visibility** through role-appropriate dashboards accessible to Admin and Procurement Manager roles, replacing periodic manual reporting.
8. **Reduce procurement-related administrative overhead**, freeing procurement staff time for vendor negotiation and strategic sourcing activity rather than repetitive data entry and manual status chasing.

---

# 14. Business Goals

Where the objectives above are specific and measurable, the business goals describe the broader strategic direction the organization is working toward by adopting VendorHub:

- To make procurement a **transparent, auditable function**, one governed by documented process rather than dependent on institutional memory and informal trust between individuals.
- To position the procurement team as a **strategic function** capable of producing spend insight and vendor performance data for leadership, rather than being viewed as a purely administrative, transactional back office.
- To build **organizational resilience** into the procurement process, so that the departure, absence, or reassignment of any single staff member does not create a gap in procurement continuity or a loss of institutional knowledge.
- To create the **data foundation** required for more advanced future procurement capabilities — such as spend forecasting or automated vendor risk scoring — which are simply not achievable without first having structured, reliable, historical procurement data.
- To improve **vendor relationships** by giving suppliers a professional, self-service channel through which to view RFQs, submit quotations, and track purchase orders, rather than relying on ad hoc, inconsistent email exchanges that can vary in quality from one procurement staff member to another.

---

# 15. Project Vision

VendorHub's vision is to become the operational backbone through which an organization manages every vendor relationship and every procurement decision — not as a passive record-keeping afterthought, but as the system that actively shapes how procurement decisions are made, documented, and subsequently reviewed.

The long-term vision extends beyond simply digitizing existing manual steps in their current form. It is to create a procurement environment in which:

- Every purchase decision is **traceable** to a specific, documented business need, a specific set of compared quotations, and a specific approving authority — leaving no ambiguity about how or why a decision was reached.
- Every vendor relationship is backed by a **quantifiable performance history**, so that vendor selection improves incrementally over time rather than remaining static and dependent on unchanging assumptions about supplier reliability.
- Procurement leadership can make **evidence-based decisions** about which vendor relationships to expand, which to review or discontinue, and where spend is concentrated — informed by real, current data rather than periodic, retrospective manual audits.

In this vision, VendorHub is not merely a system that passively records what procurement teams already do; it is a system that actively raises the standard of how procurement is conducted across the organization.

---

# 16. Project Scope

The scope of VendorHub, for the purposes of this initial release, is deliberately bounded to the core procurement lifecycle: vendor management, purchase requests, approval workflow, RFQs, quotations, purchase orders, delivery tracking, vendor rating, and procurement dashboards and reporting.

This scope has been defined directly from the business problem statement in Section 9 — every capability included within scope maps explicitly to one or more of the identified pain points of the existing manual process. Capabilities that extend beyond this core lifecycle, such as multi-currency international procurement, integrated payment processing, or contract lifecycle management, are explicitly excluded from this release and are addressed, where relevant, in the Future Roadmap (Section 38).

---

# 17. In Scope

The following capabilities are within scope for this release of VendorHub:

- User authentication and role-based access control for Admin, Procurement Manager, and Vendor roles.
- Vendor onboarding, profile management, and vendor master record maintenance, including vendor approval by Admin.
- Purchase Request creation, routing, and approval workflow.
- Request for Quotation (RFQ) creation and issuance to selected vendors, generated only from an approved purchase request.
- Vendor-side quotation submission against an issued RFQ, restricted to vendors who have been explicitly invited.
- Structured side-by-side quotation comparison for procurement decision-makers.
- Vendor selection and Purchase Order generation, restricted to approved quotations.
- Purchase Order tracking and delivery status updates by vendors.
- Vendor performance rating following order and delivery completion.
- Role-specific dashboards summarizing procurement activity and status.
- Procurement reporting covering purchase request volume, spend, vendor activity, and approval turnaround.
- User management (Admin capability to manage user accounts and roles).

---

# 18. Out of Scope

The following are explicitly excluded from this release. Their exclusion is a deliberate scoping decision, not an oversight, and each may be considered for future phases as described in Section 38.

- Integrated online payment processing or invoicing/accounts payable functionality.
- Multi-currency and multi-entity procurement for global organizations.
- Contract lifecycle management (drafting, e-signature, and legal review of vendor contracts).
- Inventory and warehouse management integration.
- Automated vendor discovery or vendor marketplace features.
- Mobile native applications (the platform will be a responsive web application, not a dedicated iOS/Android app).
- Integration with third-party ERP systems (SAP, Oracle, etc.).
- Advanced AI-based vendor risk scoring or predictive spend forecasting.
- Multi-language/localization support.

---

# 19. Stakeholders

VendorHub involves the following categories of stakeholders, each with a distinct interest in the system's success:

**Executive Sponsors / Leadership** — Interested in overall spend visibility, procurement governance, and the return on investment of digitizing procurement.

**Procurement Managers** — The primary operational users of the system, responsible for day-to-day execution of the procurement lifecycle.

**Administrators** — Responsible for system configuration, user and vendor account management, and organizational oversight.

**Vendors (External Stakeholders)** — Suppliers who interact with the platform to view RFQs, submit quotations, and track purchase orders and deliveries.

**Finance/Accounts Teams** — Indirect stakeholders who rely on accurate purchase order and spend data for budgeting and reconciliation, even though they are not direct system users in this release.

**Requesting Departments** — Internal staff across departments who raise purchase requests and depend on timely fulfillment of those requests.

**Engineering and QA Teams** — Responsible for translating this BRD into the SRS, HLD, LLD, and ultimately a working, tested system.

---

# 20. Stakeholder Responsibilities

**Executive Sponsors** are responsible for approving the business case for VendorHub, allocating the resources necessary for its development and rollout, and reviewing the procurement analytics produced by the system to guide organizational decision-making.

**Procurement Managers** are responsible for creating and managing purchase requests, issuing RFQs to appropriate vendors, comparing submitted quotations, selecting vendors, generating purchase orders, and recording vendor performance ratings upon order completion.

**Administrators** are responsible for managing user accounts and role assignments, maintaining and approving the vendor master record (including onboarding and deactivating vendors), approving purchase requests where required by organizational policy, and monitoring overall system usage through administrative dashboards and reports.

**Vendors** are responsible for maintaining accurate profile and contact information, responding to issued RFQs within the required timeframe, submitting accurate and complete quotations, and updating delivery status against the purchase orders they have been awarded.

**Finance/Accounts Teams**, while not direct system actors in this release, are responsible for consuming the purchase order and spend data generated by the system for downstream budgeting and reconciliation processes.

**Requesting Departments** are responsible for submitting purchase requests with sufficiently clear and complete business justification to allow timely review and approval.

**Engineering and QA Teams** are responsible for ensuring that the system as built faithfully reflects the requirements defined in this BRD and subsequent technical documentation, and for validating that each module meets its intended business purpose prior to release.

---

# 21. User Personas

**Persona 1: Ananya, Procurement Manager**
Ananya manages procurement for a mid-sized manufacturing division handling roughly 40–60 active purchase requests at any given time. Her biggest frustration with the current spreadsheet-based process is the time she loses manually reformatting vendor quotations into a comparison sheet before she can present a recommendation to her Admin. She needs a system that lets her see all quotations for an RFQ in one consistent view, and that keeps a record of why she selected a particular vendor, in case that decision is questioned later.

**Persona 2: Rajesh, Admin / Procurement Head**
Rajesh oversees procurement policy and approval for high-value purchase requests across the organization. He currently has no reliable way to know, at any given moment, how many purchase requests are awaiting his approval or how procurement spend is trending across departments. He needs a dashboard that gives him this visibility without having to ask his team to compile a report manually.

**Persona 3: Vikram, Vendor Representative**
Vikram represents a mid-sized supplier that regularly bids for corporate contracts. Today, he receives RFQs by email, sometimes buried among dozens of other messages, and has no reliable way to track the status of quotations he has already submitted. He wants a straightforward portal where he can see open RFQs relevant to him, submit quotations directly, and check the status of purchase orders he has been awarded.

**Persona 4: Priya, Department Requester**
Priya works in the operations department and periodically needs to raise purchase requests for equipment. Her main concern is not knowing whether her request has been seen, approved, or is simply stuck. She wants basic visibility into the status of requests she has raised, without needing to follow up by email.

---

# 22. Business Requirements

The business requirements below describe *what* the system must achieve from a business standpoint. They are intentionally expressed independent of technical implementation, which will be detailed in the SRS.

**BR-01:** The system shall maintain a single, de-duplicated vendor master record accessible to authorized roles.

**BR-02:** The system shall allow authenticated users to create purchase requests that capture the business justification, requested items or services, and requesting department.

**BR-03:** The system shall route purchase requests through a defined approval step before they can proceed to RFQ issuance.

**BR-04:** The system shall allow Procurement Managers to issue RFQs to one or more selected vendors based on an approved purchase request.

**BR-05:** The system shall allow vendors to view RFQs addressed to them and submit structured quotations in response.

**BR-06:** The system shall present submitted quotations for a given RFQ in a structured, comparable format to support vendor selection decisions.

**BR-07:** The system shall allow a Procurement Manager to select a vendor from submitted quotations and generate a Purchase Order tied to that selection.

**BR-08:** The system shall allow vendors to update the delivery status of Purchase Orders awarded to them.

**BR-09:** The system shall allow Procurement Managers to record a vendor performance rating following order completion.

**BR-10:** The system shall provide role-appropriate dashboards summarizing purchase request volume, RFQ activity, purchase order status, and vendor performance.

**BR-11:** The system shall enforce role-based access such that vendors cannot view competing vendors' quotations, and requesting departments cannot view internal approval discussion not relevant to them.

**BR-12:** The system shall maintain a traceable link between a purchase request, its associated RFQ, the compared quotations, the resulting purchase order, and the eventual vendor rating.

**BR-13:** The system shall prevent the generation of a Purchase Order from any quotation that has not been formally selected through the comparison and selection step.

**BR-14:** The system shall restrict vendor onboarding approval to the Admin role, ensuring that no vendor becomes eligible to receive RFQs without explicit organizational sign-off.

---

# 23. Functional Overview

At a functional level, VendorHub is organized around the sequential stages of the procurement lifecycle, with each stage owned primarily by a specific role but remaining visible, where appropriate, to other roles to preserve transparency across the process.

The **Admin** functions primarily as the governance layer of the system: managing who has access, maintaining and approving the vendor master record, and, depending on organizational policy, providing final approval on purchase requests above a defined value threshold. Admin-facing functionality is oriented toward oversight and control rather than high-frequency transactional activity.

The **Procurement Manager** functions as the operational engine of the system, executing the core lifecycle from purchase request through to purchase order and vendor rating. Their functional needs are oriented toward speed and clarity — moving a request through each stage with minimal friction while retaining a complete, retrievable audit trail at every step.

The **Vendor** functions as an external participant with a narrower, self-service functional scope: viewing relevant RFQs, submitting quotations, and updating delivery status. Vendor-facing functionality is deliberately kept simple and intuitive, since vendors are external parties and should not require formal training to use the platform effectively.

Underlying all three roles is a shared functional thread that defines the platform's core value: every action taken in the system — a request submitted, an RFQ issued, a quotation submitted, a purchase order generated, a rating recorded — becomes part of a persistent, traceable record, rather than a transient email exchange or an unrecorded conversation.

---

# 24. Business Workflow

The end-to-end business workflow that VendorHub digitizes follows a consistent, enforced sequence. Each step below is explained in terms of its business purpose, not merely its position in the sequence.

**Step 1 — Authentication.** Users authenticate into the system according to their assigned role (Admin, Procurement Manager, or Vendor). This is the gatekeeping step for every subsequent action in the workflow; access from this point forward is scoped strictly according to the authenticated user's role, ensuring that no downstream action is available to a user who is not authorized to perform it.

**Step 2 — Dashboard.** Immediately following authentication, the user is presented with a role-appropriate dashboard summarizing the state of the procurement activity relevant to them — pending approvals for an Admin, active RFQs and comparisons for a Procurement Manager, or open RFQs and awarded orders for a Vendor. This step exists to give every user immediate operational context without requiring them to navigate the system to discover what needs their attention.

**Step 3 — Vendor Management.** Before procurement activity involving a given vendor can begin, that vendor must exist as an approved record in the system, onboarded and approved by an Admin. This step establishes the vendor master record described in Section 12 as the single source of truth for vendor identity.

**Step 4 — Purchase Request.** A requesting department or Procurement Manager raises a purchase request describing the business need, the items or services required, and the justification for the purchase. This step formally initiates the procurement cycle and creates the first traceable record in the chain described in BR-12.

**Step 5 — Approval Workflow.** The purchase request is routed to the appropriate approving authority according to organizational policy. This step exists specifically to prevent unauthorized or unjustified spend from proceeding further into the process, and it replaces the untracked, easily-lost email approval described in Section 11.

**Step 6 — Request for Quotation (RFQ).** Once a purchase request is approved, the Procurement Manager issues an RFQ to one or more relevant vendors, formalizing the informal "asking vendors for pricing" step into a structured, trackable request.

**Step 7 — Vendor Quotation Submission.** Invited vendors respond to the RFQ by submitting structured quotations covering price, delivery timeline, and terms, through the vendor-facing self-service portal rather than by email attachment.

**Step 8 — Quotation Comparison.** The Procurement Manager reviews all submitted quotations for a given RFQ side by side, in a consistent structured format, to evaluate price, delivery timeline, and vendor reliability without manual transcription.

**Step 9 — Vendor Selection.** Based on this comparison, the Procurement Manager formally selects the winning vendor for the request, and this selection becomes the documented justification referenced by BR-13.

**Step 10 — Purchase Order Generation.** A formal Purchase Order is generated, referencing the originating purchase request, the RFQ, and the selected quotation, establishing the complete traceable chain from business need to formal commitment.

**Step 11 — Delivery Tracking.** The awarded vendor updates delivery status against the Purchase Order as fulfillment progresses, giving both the vendor and the Procurement Manager shared, real-time visibility into order progress.

**Step 12 — Vendor Rating.** Upon confirmed delivery completion, the Procurement Manager records a performance rating for the vendor, contributing to that vendor's ongoing, cumulative performance history as referenced in BR-09.

**Step 13 — Reports.** Procurement Managers and Admins can generate filtered reports covering purchase request volume, spend by department or category, vendor activity, and approval turnaround, replacing the periodic manual compilation described in Section 11.

**Step 14 — Analytics Dashboard.** Aggregated, real-time analytics — trends in spend, vendor performance over time, and approval cycle times — are continuously reflected back to Admin and Procurement Manager roles, closing the loop between operational activity and strategic insight.

This workflow is the structural backbone of the entire platform; every module described in Section 26 exists to support one or more steps in this sequence, and every business rule described in Section 27 exists to protect the integrity of this sequence.

---

# 25. Business Process Flow

While Section 24 describes the business workflow from the perspective of *what happens and why*, this section illustrates the *flow of the process across organizational participants* — showing how a single purchase need moves from an internal department, through competitive vendor engagement, to a completed and rated purchase order.

```
Department
   │
   ▼
Purchase Request
   │
   ▼
Approval
   │
   ▼
Request for Quotation (RFQ)
   │
   ├──────────────┬──────────────┐
   ▼              ▼              ▼
Vendor A       Vendor B       Vendor C
   │              │              │
   └──────────────┴──────────────┘
                  │
                  ▼
         Quotation Comparison
                  │
                  ▼
            Vendor Selection
                  │
                  ▼
             Purchase Order
                  │
                  ▼
                Delivery
                  │
                  ▼
             Vendor Rating
                  │
                  ▼
                Dashboard
```

**Explanation of the flow.** The process begins within a requesting **Department**, which identifies a genuine business need and raises a **Purchase Request**. This request does not proceed further until it clears **Approval**, which acts as a control gate ensuring that only justified, authorized spend enters the procurement pipeline. Once approved, the request is converted into an **RFQ**, which is distributed simultaneously to multiple qualified vendors — illustrated here as Vendor A, Vendor B, and Vendor C — rather than to a single supplier chosen without competitive comparison. This is a deliberate design principle: wherever feasible, procurement decisions should be informed by more than one data point.

Each invited vendor responds independently, and their submissions converge back into a single **Quotation Comparison** step, where the Procurement Manager evaluates all responses on a like-for-like basis. This comparison directly informs **Vendor Selection**, which in turn generates a formal **Purchase Order** — the point at which the organization's commitment to a specific vendor becomes official and traceable. From there, the process moves into **Delivery**, tracked jointly by the vendor and the Procurement Manager, and concludes with a **Vendor Rating** that feeds back into the vendor's cumulative performance record. Every stage of this flow ultimately surfaces in the **Dashboard**, ensuring that no part of the process happens outside of organizational visibility.

This flow makes explicit a principle that is easy to lose in a manual, email-based process: procurement is not a single decision made by one person in isolation, but a structured, multi-party process with defined checkpoints, each of which exists to protect the organization from an identifiable risk — unauthorized spend, uncompetitive vendor selection, or undocumented decision-making.

---

# 26. Module Overview

**Authentication Module.** Provides secure login and role assignment, forming the entry point through which all access control in the system is enforced. Its business purpose is to ensure that sensitive procurement and pricing data is only visible to those authorized to see it.

**User Management Module.** Allows Administrators to create, modify, and deactivate user accounts and assign roles. This exists to give the organization direct control over who can act as an approver, a procurement manager, or a system administrator, rather than relying on informal trust.

**Vendor Management Module.** Maintains the vendor master record — profiles, contact details, tax identifiers, and status (active/inactive/pending approval). This module directly addresses the duplicate and inconsistent vendor record problem identified in Section 9, by establishing a single authoritative source for vendor identity.

**Purchase Request Management Module.** Captures and tracks purchase requests from creation through approval. This module replaces the email-based request process with a system-tracked workflow that gives requesters visibility into status and gives approvers a queue of pending decisions.

**Approval Workflow Module.** Manages the routing, status, and escalation of purchase requests awaiting approval, ensuring that every request has a defined, current state and a named accountable approver at all times, and providing the control gate described in the Business Process Flow.

**RFQ Management Module.** Enables Procurement Managers to formalize an approved purchase request into a structured request sent to one or more vendors, replacing ad hoc individual emails with a consistent, trackable RFQ issuance process.

**Quotation Management Module.** Allows invited vendors to submit quotations against an RFQ and allows Procurement Managers to view and compare them in a structured format, directly addressing the manual quotation comparison pain point.

**Purchase Order Management Module.** Generates and tracks Purchase Orders resulting from vendor selection, maintaining a clear link back to the request and quotation that justified the order, and supporting delivery status tracking through to completion.

**Vendor Rating Module.** Captures structured performance feedback following order completion, building a cumulative, queryable performance history for each vendor rather than relying on informal team recollection.

**Dashboard Module.** Aggregates data across all modules into role-appropriate real-time views, replacing periodic manual reporting with continuous visibility.

**Reports Module.** Provides deeper, filterable reporting on procurement activity — spend by department or category, vendor activity, and approval turnaround — supporting the analytical needs identified as missing from the existing manual system.

**Analytics Dashboard Module.** Extends the standard Dashboard Module with trend-oriented views — spend trajectory over time, vendor performance trends, and approval cycle-time trends — giving leadership a forward-looking view of procurement health rather than only a point-in-time snapshot.

---

# 27. Business Rules

The following business rules govern the behavior of the platform and exist to protect the integrity of the procurement process described in Sections 24 and 25. These rules are business-level constraints; their specific technical enforcement mechanism will be detailed in the SRS.

1. **Vendor email addresses must be unique** across the vendor master record, preventing the same vendor from being inadvertently or deliberately onboarded more than once under a different profile.
2. **Vendor GST (or equivalent tax registration) numbers must be unique**, providing a secondary safeguard against duplicate vendor records beyond email address alone.
3. **Only the Admin role may approve a new vendor** into the vendor master record; a vendor profile cannot become eligible to receive RFQs without explicit Admin sign-off.
4. **Purchase Requests require formal approval** before they may proceed to RFQ issuance; no RFQ may be generated from an unapproved request.
5. **RFQs can only be created from an approved Purchase Request**, preserving the traceability chain described in BR-12.
6. **Only vendors explicitly invited to a given RFQ may submit a quotation against it**, ensuring that quotation comparison is limited to vendors the organization has deliberately chosen to engage for that specific request.
7. **Purchase Orders can only be generated from a quotation that has been formally selected** through the Vendor Selection step; a Purchase Order cannot be issued directly against an unreviewed or unselected quotation.
8. **Vendor ratings may only be recorded after delivery completion** has been confirmed against the relevant Purchase Order, ensuring that performance feedback reflects actual fulfillment rather than an in-progress or speculative assessment.
9. **Users may only access modules and data consistent with their assigned role**, in accordance with BR-11; a Vendor, for example, can never view another vendor's submitted quotation.
10. **Delete operations must be implemented as soft deletes wherever the deleted record participates in the audit trail** (vendors, purchase requests, RFQs, quotations, and purchase orders), preserving historical traceability even where a record is no longer active.
11. **A Purchase Request cannot be edited by the requester once it has entered the approval workflow**, preventing the approved scope of a request from silently diverging from what an approver actually reviewed and authorized.
12. **An RFQ cannot be reopened for additional quotation submissions once a vendor has been formally selected**, ensuring the integrity of the comparison that informed the selection decision.
13. **A vendor that has been deactivated by an Admin can no longer be invited to new RFQs**, though their historical record and performance history remain retrievable for audit and reporting purposes.
14. **Every state-changing action performed on a purchase request, RFQ, quotation, or purchase order must be attributable to the specific user who performed it**, forming the basis of the platform's audit trail.

---

# 28. Key Success Factors

The following factors have been identified as critical to VendorHub achieving its intended business impact. These are qualities the platform must demonstrably possess, rather than features to be checked off a list:

- **Ease of use.** The platform must be intuitive enough that Procurement Managers and requesting departments require minimal training to become productive, and that vendors — who are external to the organization — can use the portal without formal onboarding support.
- **Fast procurement workflow.** Every step in the digitized workflow must be demonstrably faster than its manual equivalent; if using the system is slower than sending an email, adoption will fail regardless of the platform's other qualities.
- **Responsive user interface.** The platform must perform reliably and remain visually clear across the range of devices and screen sizes procurement staff and vendors are likely to use, given that the initial release targets a responsive web application rather than a native mobile app.
- **Secure authentication.** Given that the platform handles commercially sensitive vendor pricing and internal approval data, authentication and access control must be robust and consistently enforced across every module.
- **Scalable architecture.** While the current release is scoped to a modular monolithic architecture appropriate to expected launch-scale usage, the underlying design must not preclude reasonable growth in purchase volume, vendor count, and user base without requiring a full re-architecture.
- **Effective reporting.** Reports and dashboards must surface genuinely decision-useful information — not just raw data — allowing leadership to act on procurement insight rather than simply viewing it.
- **Reduced paperwork.** The platform must measurably reduce the organization's dependence on manually generated documents (spreadsheets, printed purchase orders, email chains) as the primary record of procurement activity.
- **Improved transparency.** At every stage of the procurement lifecycle, relevant stakeholders must be able to see current status without needing to ask another individual directly, replacing the opacity of the current email-based process.

---

# 29. Success Criteria

The success of VendorHub, from a business standpoint, will be evaluated against the following measurable Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) following rollout, benchmarked against the historical baseline established under the manual, spreadsheet-and-email process:

- **Reduce procurement processing time.** Measure and reduce the average time elapsed from purchase request submission to purchase order issuance, compared to the historical baseline.
- **Reduce duplicate vendor records.** Achieve and maintain zero duplicate vendor records in the vendor master, enforced through the uniqueness rules defined in Section 27.
- **Increase procurement transparency.** Achieve full status visibility for 100% of purchase requests in flight, eliminating the "unknown status" condition common under the manual process.
- **Reduce paperwork.** Measurably reduce the volume of manually generated procurement documents (spreadsheets, printed POs, standalone email approvals) required to complete a procurement cycle.
- **Improve vendor response tracking.** Achieve consistent, system-recorded visibility into vendor response times to issued RFQs, a data point that is not reliably captured under the manual process at all.
- **Improve approval turnaround.** Reduce the average time a purchase request spends awaiting approval, and eliminate requests that stall indefinitely without any recorded status.
- **Generate reports instantly.** Reduce the time required to produce a procurement spend or activity report from a multi-day manual compilation exercise to an on-demand, real-time query.
- **Improve vendor performance evaluation.** Ensure that vendor selection decisions can reference a documented performance rating history for at least all vendors who have completed one or more prior orders through the platform.
- **Achieve a documented, retrievable audit trail** for 100% of purchase orders issued through the platform, linking each order back to its originating request and quotation comparison.
- **Achieve measurable adoption** of the vendor rating module, evidenced by a rating being recorded for every completed purchase order within a defined post-delivery window.

---

# 30. Business Assumptions

This BRD is prepared on the basis of the following assumptions, which stakeholders should validate during the review process:

- The organization has a defined, if informal, approval hierarchy for purchase requests that can be reasonably encoded into the system's approval workflow.
- Vendors engaging with the platform have basic access to email and a web browser, sufficient to receive login credentials and interact with the vendor-facing portal.
- The initial rollout will be for a single organizational entity, not a multi-subsidiary or multi-currency group structure.
- Purchase request volume at launch is within a range where a modular monolithic architecture (rather than a distributed microservices system) provides sufficient performance and scalability.
- Organizational stakeholders are prepared to transition away from email-based procurement communication as the primary channel, in favor of the platform.
- Legal and compliance teams have no objection, at this stage, to procurement records being stored within this system rather than a pre-existing ERP or document management system.

---

# 31. Constraints

- **Budget and timeline constraints** typical of a first-release platform limit the scope to the core lifecycle defined in Section 17, deferring more advanced capabilities to future phases.
- **Technology constraint:** the system is built on the MERN stack with a modular monolithic architecture, which constrains certain scalability approaches (e.g., independent scaling of individual modules) that would be available under a microservices approach, though this is not considered a limiting factor at the anticipated scale of initial deployment.
- **Organizational constraint:** successful adoption depends on procurement staff and department requesters actually shifting their behavior away from email-based workflows, which may require change management effort beyond the scope of the software itself.
- **Vendor-side constraint:** the platform's effectiveness for RFQ and quotation management depends on vendor willingness and ability to engage with a new digital portal rather than continuing to respond by email.
- **Single-entity constraint:** the initial release does not support multi-entity or multi-currency operations, which may limit applicability for organizations with international procurement needs.

---

# 32. Risks

**Risk 1 — Low vendor adoption.** Vendors accustomed to email-based communication may be slow to adopt the vendor portal, undermining the RFQ and quotation workflow that depends on their participation.

**Risk 2 — Incomplete migration of existing vendor data.** If historical vendor records are not accurately migrated from existing spreadsheets, the vendor master record may itself begin with duplicate or inconsistent data, weakening one of the platform's core value propositions.

**Risk 3 — Approval workflow misalignment.** If the system's approval workflow does not accurately reflect the organization's actual (and sometimes informal) approval hierarchy, users may attempt to bypass the system, reverting to manual approval outside the platform.

**Risk 4 — Change resistance from procurement staff.** Staff accustomed to spreadsheet-based processes may resist transitioning to a new system, particularly if the perceived learning curve outweighs the perceived benefit in the short term.

**Risk 5 — Data security concerns.** Procurement data includes commercially sensitive vendor pricing; inadequate access control could expose competitive quotation data to unauthorized parties, damaging vendor trust in the platform.

**Risk 6 — Scope creep.** Given the broad appeal of procurement digitization, there is a risk that stakeholders request the inclusion of out-of-scope capabilities (Section 18) mid-development, delaying the core release.

---

# 33. Risk Mitigation

**For low vendor adoption (Risk 1):** Provide a simple, low-friction vendor onboarding process and, where feasible, run an initial pilot with a small group of high-engagement vendors before full rollout, using their experience to refine the vendor-facing workflow.

**For incomplete vendor data migration (Risk 2):** Conduct a structured data cleansing and de-duplication exercise on existing vendor spreadsheets prior to migration, with Admin sign-off on the cleaned vendor master before go-live.

**For approval workflow misalignment (Risk 3):** Validate the proposed approval workflow directly with Admin and Procurement Manager stakeholders during the requirements review stage (this BRD cycle) rather than after development, and allow for configurable approval thresholds where organizational policy requires it.

**For change resistance (Risk 4):** Pair the rollout with structured training sessions and clear communication of the specific pain points (Section 9) the system addresses, framing adoption around tangible time savings rather than presenting it as a compliance mandate alone.

**For data security concerns (Risk 5):** Enforce strict role-based access control (as captured in BR-11) from the outset, ensuring vendors can never view competing quotations and that pricing data is scoped strictly to authorized internal roles.

**For scope creep (Risk 6):** Maintain firm adherence to the In Scope / Out of Scope boundaries defined in Sections 17 and 18, routing any new requests through a formal change request process rather than informal addition to the current release.

---

# 34. Benefits

VendorHub delivers benefits across several dimensions of the procurement function:

**Operational efficiency.** By replacing manual quotation transcription and email-based approval chains with structured system workflows, procurement staff spend less time on administrative overhead and more time on vendor engagement and negotiation.

**Data integrity.** A single vendor master record eliminates the duplication and inconsistency that plague spreadsheet-based tracking, ensuring that spend and performance data reflects reality rather than fragmented partial records.

**Accountability and auditability.** Every purchase request, RFQ, quotation, and purchase order is linked and traceable, meaning that vendor selection decisions can be justified with evidence rather than recollection — an important benefit in the event of internal audit or stakeholder inquiry.

**Improved vendor relationships.** A dedicated vendor portal gives suppliers a professional, self-service channel to engage with the organization, which can improve response times and overall vendor satisfaction.

**Leadership visibility.** Real-time dashboards give leadership immediate insight into procurement activity and spend trends, without waiting for periodic manual reports.

**Foundation for future capability.** The structured data VendorHub produces — vendor performance history, spend patterns, approval turnaround times — becomes the foundation for more advanced future capabilities described in Section 38.

---

# 35. Expected Outcomes

Following successful implementation and adoption of VendorHub, the organization can expect:

- A measurable reduction in the cycle time between purchase request submission and purchase order issuance.
- A clean, de-duplicated, continuously maintained vendor master record.
- Elimination of the manual, error-prone process of transcribing vendor quotations into comparison spreadsheets.
- A complete, retrievable audit trail for every procurement decision made through the platform.
- The ability to generate spend and vendor performance reports on demand, rather than through periodic manual compilation.
- A documented history of vendor performance that can directly inform future vendor selection and negotiation.
- Reduced dependency on any single individual's institutional knowledge to keep the procurement process functioning.

---

# 36. Business Value

The business value of VendorHub extends beyond the direct efficiency gains of digitizing an existing process. By making procurement data structured and queryable for the first time, the organization gains the ability to answer strategic questions it previously could not answer at all — not just "did we make this purchase" but "is this vendor relationship performing well over time," "which departments are driving the most procurement volume," and "where are approval delays actually occurring."

This shift — from procurement as an administrative record-keeping function to procurement as a source of strategic business intelligence — is the core business value proposition of the platform. It positions the procurement function to contribute more directly to organizational cost management and vendor strategy, rather than being viewed purely as a transactional support function.

Additionally, by reducing the manual administrative burden on procurement staff, the organization creates capacity within its existing team to take on higher-value activities — vendor negotiation, strategic sourcing initiatives, and vendor relationship management — without requiring proportional headcount growth as purchase volume increases.

---

# 37. Project Deliverables

The following deliverables constitute the complete output of the VendorHub project and will be provided at project completion:

- **Web Application** — the fully functional VendorHub platform, covering the Admin, Procurement Manager, and Vendor experiences described throughout this document.
- **Source Code** — the complete, version-controlled codebase for the frontend and backend, organized according to the modular monolithic architecture described in Section 12.
- **Documentation** — the full documentation suite, including this Business Requirement Document, the System Requirement Specification, High-Level Design, and Low-Level Design.
- **REST APIs** — the backend API layer supporting all functional modules described in Section 26, documented for use by frontend and any future integration efforts.
- **Admin Dashboard** — the role-specific administrative interface supporting user management, vendor approval, and organizational oversight.
- **Vendor Portal** — the dedicated, self-service interface through which vendors engage with RFQs, submit quotations, and track purchase orders.
- **Reports** — the reporting module output, covering purchase request volume, spend, vendor activity, and approval turnaround as described in Section 26.
- **Deployment Guide** — documentation covering environment setup, configuration, and release process for the platform.
- **Presentation** — a stakeholder-facing presentation summarizing the project's business rationale, scope, and outcomes, suitable for project review or expo settings.
- **Project Report** — a consolidated written account of the project's objectives, execution, and outcomes.
- **GitHub Repository** — the hosted, version-controlled repository containing the complete source code and commit history for the project.

---

# 38. Future Roadmap

While the current release of VendorHub is intentionally scoped to the core procurement lifecycle (Section 17), several capabilities have been identified as candidates for future phases, contingent on separate business case approval:

- **Vendor self-registration with Admin approval**, reducing the administrative burden of manual vendor onboarding.
- **Integration with accounting/ERP systems** for automated invoice reconciliation against purchase orders.
- **Contract lifecycle management**, extending the platform beyond purchase orders into formal vendor contract drafting and renewal tracking.
- **Advanced analytics**, including spend forecasting and vendor risk scoring based on historical performance data.
- **Multi-entity and multi-currency support**, extending applicability to organizations with international procurement operations.
- **Mobile application support**, extending access beyond the responsive web application to dedicated mobile experiences for approvers who need to act on requests while away from a desktop.
- **Automated vendor performance alerts**, flagging vendors whose ratings fall below an organizational threshold for proactive review.

These items are recorded here to ensure they are not lost from consideration, while remaining explicitly out of scope for the current release as defined in Section 18.

---

# 39. Glossary

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| BRD | Business Requirement Document — this document, capturing business-level requirements prior to technical design. |
| RFQ | Request for Quotation — a formal request sent to vendors asking them to submit pricing and terms for specified goods or services. |
| Purchase Request | An internal request raised by a department or staff member to initiate a procurement need. |
| Purchase Order (PO) | A formal, system-generated document confirming the organization's commitment to purchase from a selected vendor under agreed terms. |
| Vendor Master Record | The authoritative, de-duplicated record of all vendors an organization engages with. |
| Vendor Rating | A structured performance score recorded for a vendor following completion of a purchase order. |
| Procurement Lifecycle | The full sequence of steps from purchase request through vendor selection, purchase order issuance, delivery, and vendor rating. |
| Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) | A security model in which system access is scoped according to a user's assigned role. |
| Soft Delete | A deletion approach in which a record is marked inactive rather than permanently removed, preserving it for audit and historical traceability purposes. |
| S2P | Source-to-Pay — the broader category of procurement software covering sourcing through payment. |
| SRM | Supplier Relationship Management — the broader discipline of managing ongoing vendor relationships. |

---

# 40. References

This document was prepared based on internal stakeholder interviews with procurement staff, review of the existing spreadsheet- and email-based procurement process, and general industry context regarding Source-to-Pay and Supplier Relationship Management software categories. No external proprietary data sources were used in the preparation of this BRD. Subsequent technical documentation (SRS, HLD, LLD) should be treated as the authoritative reference for implementation-level detail not covered here.

---

# 41. Conclusion

VendorHub addresses a well-defined and consistently observed business problem: the operational fragility and lack of visibility that results from managing procurement through spreadsheets, email, and manual paperwork. Rather than proposing a broad, feature-heavy platform that attempts to replicate the full breadth of enterprise Source-to-Pay suites, this document has scoped VendorHub deliberately around the core procurement lifecycle — vendor management, purchase requests, approval workflow, RFQs, quotations, purchase orders, delivery tracking, and vendor rating — because this is the sequence of activity where the existing manual process demonstrably fails.

The business requirements, business rules, scope boundaries, stakeholder responsibilities, and risk mitigations captured in this document are intended to give engineering and design teams a clear, traceable foundation from which to develop the System Requirement Specification and subsequent technical design artifacts. Every module, business rule, and requirement described here maps directly back to a specific pain point identified in the Business Problem Statement (Section 9), ensuring that the system ultimately built is judged not by feature count, but by how directly and measurably it resolves the operational failures it was commissioned to solve.

With stakeholder sign-off on this BRD, the project is ready to proceed to the next phase of formal system design.

